<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-497-592  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 497 592.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 24 1990 n1215 p19(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>When will we reach the point of no return? (evaluating systems andthe bottom line)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harvey, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Companies are curtailing their expenditures on MIS as theystruggle to justify MIS expenses at the bottom line.andO;Increasingly, systems are viewed in the context of business, andtheir relevance is questioned at the boardroom level.andP;  In thepast, predictable savings resulted from computerization.andP;  Now,systems are acquired for such intangible, uncertain, andimmeasurable benefits as competitive advantage.andP;  In the future,MIS will become either another corporate service or a front-linebusiness tool, depending on its ability to demonstrateindisputable benefits.andP;  In the US, the meteoric elevation of chiefinformation officers ended when the right solutions failed toappear.andP;  A similar corporate enthusiasm for MIS directors hasbegun in the UK.andP;  These appointees face tough issues, and couldeither throw new light on old problems or become convenientscapegoats.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Industry AnalysisUnited KingdomMISManagement of EDPCostEnd UsersFuture of ComputingCompanies.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>